subSubSection.paragraph:
Head (
Fig. 9A
) covered with sparse setiferous punctures; setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 10C
); frontoclypeal suture bisinuate, middle portion narrow, about one-third width of clypeus; labrum and clypeus convex and furnished with setae; length of clypeus longer than that of labrum. Canthus large, acutely triangular but apex rounded. Apex of mandible bifurcate and furnished with three teeth apically on inner margin; lateral angles furnished with setae (
Fig. 8D
). Antennae long; segments short, except for first, third, and fourth which are long and slender, and eleventh which is pointed; all segments setous, fifth through eleventh segments with shorter, denser setae (
Fig. 8C
).

Pronotum (
Fig. 8A
, 
9B
) with blunt lateral tubercles, strongly tapered towards base; groove of anterior margin distinctly impressed a narrow distance from margin; posterior marginal groove undulate and complete; lateral basal angles swollen and with two to five long setae near base; surface regularly convex and with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, densely covered with coarse setiferous punctures (
Fig. 10B
); distance between punctures on central portion 1.5–3 times their own diameter, denser laterally. Setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 10B
).

Elytra short, leaving apex of pygidium exposed, moderately vaulted in lateral view; lateral sides ovate, widening approaching posterior margin; dorsal surface with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture (
Fig. 10D
), irregularly covered with dense setiferous punctures which are as coarse as on pronotum and separated by 1–3 times their diameter; setae produced just anterior to punctures (
Fig. 10D
); sutural and lateral grooves complete from elytral base to apex; basal areas of elytra weakly convex on either side of suture; humerus strongly protruding anteriorly; epipleuron narrow. Scutellum trapezoidal, with setae.

Disc of mesoventrite rugose; process densely furnished with setiferous punctures (
Fig. 8B
, 
9C
). Mesepisternum furnished with setiferous punctures except on posteroventral margin (
Fig. 8B
, 
9C
). Surface of metaventrite with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture (
Fig. 10C
), central area covered with setiferous punctures, becoming denser on lateral portions, setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 10C
). Surface of sternites with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, sparsely covered with setiferous punctures. In male, posterior margin of 7th sternite evenly curved (
Fig. 9D
). In female, posterior margin of 7th sternite straight, but bisinuate on central portion (
Fig. 9E
).

Male genitalia as shown in 
Fig. 11
A–F: 8th sternite furnished with setae, cylindrical, membrane long, allowing for posterior horizontal extension (
Fig. 11E, F
); spiculum fan-shaped (
Fig. 11D
); median struts of median lobe approximately 2.2 times as long as median lobe (
Fig. 11A
); apex of median lobe pointed and inclined to one side (
Fig. 11B
); paramere not developed (
Fig. 11C
).
